 the experiences of a group of middle-class women in Tokyo who participated in a weekly support meeting for families of substance abusers at a public mental-health clinic. Amy Borovoy deftly analyzes the dilemmas of being female in modern Japan and the grace with which women struggle within a system that supports wives and mothers but thwarts their attempts to find fulfillment outside the family. The central concerns of the book reach beyond the problem of alcoholism to examine the women's own processes of self-reflection and criticism and the deeper fissures and asymmetries that undergird Japanese productivity and social order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAlcoholicsxFamily relationshipszJapanzTokyo. 0aAlcoholics' spouseszJapanzTokyo. 0aCodependencyzJapanzTokyo. 0aParents of drug addictszJapanzTokyo. 0aSex rolezJapanzTokyo. 0aSocial work with womenzJapanzTokyo. 0aWiveszJapanzTokyo. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aalcohol.  aalcoholics.  aalcoholism.  acodependency.  acodependent relationships.  acultural issues.  adestructive behavior.  adrunkenness.  aenabling.  afamily life.  afamily relationships.  agender issues.  agender norms.  ajapan.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese women.  amarriage.  amen and women.  amental health issues.  amiddle class.  anurturance.  apolitics of marriage.  apostwar japan.  apublic life.  asobriety.  asocial drinking.  asocial order.  asubstance abuse.  atokyo.  awives and mothers.  awives.  awomens roles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024452840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093868740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938687423Coveruhttps://www.deg